column9:
1) Can fossil pollen records be used
to examine past variations in functional attributes;
2) can community- level, functional responses to fire be obtained by coupling fire history with pollen-derived plant traits;
3) has directional selection promoted attributes that increase community flammability?

1) Develop a reconstruction method based on modern surface pollen; 
2) compare its performance with biomization; 
3) validate the method using modern and fossil pollen; 
4) reconstruct European vegetation changes.

1) Develop a universal pollen–PFT–biome framework; 
2) validate it using modern pollen; 
3) reconstruct European vegetation at 6 ka BP; 
4) demonstrate its usefulness for climate-model evaluation.

1) Diversity components (richness, 
evenness, functional and phylogenetic diversity) all convey 
independent additional information and show varying trends through
 the 14 500-yr period; 
2) The Late Glacial (LG) and the Holocene have contrasting values in diversity owing to climatic differences; 
3) Diversity components are influenced differently by climate and human impact.

1) to reveal how the functions of terrestrial vegetation and the strategies for resource acquisition within plant communities changed under climate change; 
2) how changes in the vegetation functioning and the PFTrs related to human activities; and 
3) whether Neolithic human activities accelerated, slowed down or reversed ecosystem change.

1) To compile a comprehensive modern and fossil pollen dataset
 for China; 
2) to test the applicability of the biomization method
 across a complex topoclimatic template; 
3) to document regional
 shifts in ecosystems during the mid-Holocene and Last Glacial
 Maximum; 
4) and to provide standardized data for testing global
 climate models.
